ons. The book argues that the same lollards who were used to strengthen the English church in the sixteenth century would play a role in its fragmentation in the seventeenth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLollards. 0aReformationxEarly movementsxInfluence. 0aReformationzEngland. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Tudor & Elizabethan Era (1485-1603).2bisacsh  aEarly Modern Britain.  aHistory.  aJohn Bale.  aJohn Foxe.  aJohn Wycliff.  aLollards.  aRadicalism.  aReformation England.  aReligious Culture.  aWilliam Tyndale.1 aRoyal, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612881240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526128812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526128812/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles